data.name: labelTemplateFilename.ToolTip
data.value: The filename of the template. You don't need to write “.json” at the end.

data.name: labelTextureSegAddr.ToolTip
data.value:
Where the texture is located in RAM.
In order to find it, you can use either kataraktaCS's Texture Search, or Quad64. Though, keep in mind that Texture Search is still WIP, so you might have to use Quad64 in certain cases.
For Texture Search, go to the location where the needed texture is loaded, hit “Scan for Textures,” select the texture on the list and copy the segmented address. Make sure you are copying the segmented address, not the virtual address below.
For Quad64, open the ROM of your game, go to the level where the needed texture is located, then open “Textures,” select the texture and copy the segmented address. Make sure you are copying the segmented address, not the ROM address above.

data.name: labelTextureFormat.ToolTip
data.value:
The format of the texture in RAM.
Found the same way the segmented address is found through kataraktaCS's Texture Search or Quad64.

data.name: labelTextureAltFilename.ToolTip
data.value: The filename that can be used instead of a texture pack filename (very useful if you're making a template only for RAM, for example).

data.name: checkTextureDisplay.ToolTip
data.value:
When previewing all the textures that the template has, do we show this texture?
You can turn this off for identical textures as to not clog up the texture preview.

data.name: labelTexturePackFilename.ToolTip
data.value:
For texture packs. The filename that graphics plugins use to determine what texture to change.
Please note that the game name and extension will be automatically removed. So, something like “SUPER MARIO 64#6B8D43C4#0#2_all.png” will become just “#6B8D43C4#0#2_all” for example. This is done in order to let you use texture packs on different games and ROM hacks, whose names could be different from “SUPER MARIO 64.”

data.name: labelFolderSettingsTemplateUsed.ToolTip
data.value: Select the template that will be used to identify textures inside this folder.

data.name: checkFolderSettingsCoverSubfolders.ToolTip
data.value:
Whether these Folder Settings will apply across every subfolder of this folder.
Example: Suppose you have three folders with textures in them: • Eyes\Angry\ • Eyes\Angry\Very Angry\ • Eyes\Angry\Extremely Angry\
Notice how “Very Angry” and “Extremely Angry” are subfolders of “Angry.” If you were to create Folder Settings for “Angry” and turn this option on, then the template used for “Angry” will apply for “Very Angry” and “Extremely Angry” as well.

data.name: labelSelectSomething.Text
data.value: Select a Folder Settings file or a template file to show their properties that can be modified.
